@database "DBImport Guide"
@author "Heiko Schröder"
@$VER: 3.0 (Release 3)
@wordwrap

@node main "Database Import V1.0"
                               @{" < Table of Contents " link "Macro-Package.guide/Main"}

@{fg shine}Benefits:@{fg text}
   Are you also looking for an import filter for a special database?
   Unfortunately the filters are limited to only the well known databases
   and spreadsheet calculators.

   This macro uses a little trick.
   Almost any database and spreadsheet program can export data as ASCII-text.
   The macro then reads the data and imports it into a FW-table.
   Because of this it's compatible with almost all programs...

@{fg shine}Requirements:@{fg text}
   »Final Writer 5« or better

@{fg shine}Using the @{"macro" system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview DBImport.iff"}:@{fg text}

   In the upper part of the window you can find the current DBImport
   preference that have been set.
   You can change them with Project | @{"Preferences..." link "Voreinst"} as you like.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

   @{fg fill}A@{fg text}pply
      Pressing this button starts the data importation by selecting an export
      file. The table will then be placed with its upper border right at the
      edge of the visible screen.

      If you have selected to split the data table (see @{"Preferences..." link "Voreinst"}),
      a window will appear. Enter here the desired number of rows per page.

      For an optional caption of the 1st row and/or 1st column enter the text
      in the appropriate window. The text is used for all the created tables. 

   @{fg fill}C@{fg text}ancel
   @{fg fill}ESC@{fg text} or close window
      Terminates the macro.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

@{fg shine}Note:@{fg text}
      If there are any errors while running the macro or the macro won't start
      at all please delete the file

      "S:FW_DBImport.prefs".

      In many cases this will help.
@endnode

@node Voreinst "Preferences for Database Import"

   Here you can change the layout of the table that contains the imported
   data to fit your requirements.

   @{fg fill}D@{fg text}ata Separation:
      Please enter here how the exported data items are separated from each 
      other. e.g..: , (Comma) . (Dot) - (Hyphen) d2c(9) (TAB)

   S@{fg fill}p@{fg text}lit Table:
      Sometimes there is a lot of data to import. The table that should contain
      all the data would be larger than the page size. Using this option large
      tables will be split. You are asked to enter the preferred size when you
      load the data.        

   Table A@{fg fill}l@{fg text}ignement:
      Here you can set up how to align the table in the edit area. (left, 
      centered, right)

   Table @{fg fill}W@{fg text}idth:
      Set the width of the table. 
      - automatically - the table will get the width of the edit area
      - manual        - set up table width individually

      @{fg shine}WARNING:@{fg text} Final Writer requires a column width
               of at least 0.64cm. Otherwise the data can not be imported.

         e.g.: Imagine you have a data file that contains 20 columns and you
               enter a table width of 10cm. This would result in a column
               width of 10cm/20 columns = 0.5cm per column. This won't work!
               You can now either increase the table width or you export an
               smaller number of columns. 

   @{fg fill}B@{fg text}order Size:
      Select the border size of each cell.
      No change: The value from Final Writer's preferences is used.

   Cap@{fg fill}t@{fg text}ion:
      You can add a caption to the 1st row, the 1st column of the table or to
      both of them. If you select a caption you have to enter the text after
      importing the data.

      @{fg shine}TIP:@{fg text} The easiest way to add a caption is to enter
           the text in the spreadsheet before exporting it!

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

   @{fg fill}S@{fg text}ave
      The values are saved for future use in the file "S:FW_DBImport.prefs".
      If you start the macro again the values are automatically read from this
      file.

   @{fg fill}A@{fg text}pply
      The values are only used for this session. If you start the macro again
      the old values are restored.

   @{fg fill}C@{fg text}ancel
      Reset all the values to the last saved values.

@endnode
